happiness.

00:43:47.569 --> 00:43:55.079
So, wanted to take a step back from all this
business talk and actually have you guys think

00:43:55.079 --> 00:44:03.579
about this question, "What is your goal in
life?" And, and so whatever your actual answer

00:44:03.579 --> 00:44:07.359
is, think about that. And what's interesting
is that if you actually asked different people

00:44:07.359 --> 00:44:11.109
this question, you'll get all sorts of different
answers. Some people will say, "To grow a

00:44:11.109 --> 00:44:15.290
company." Some people will say, "To get a
great job." Or, "Get a boyfriend/girlfriend."

00:44:15.290 --> 00:44:21.370
And then, ask yourself, "Why?" So, whatever
you had as your goal in life, ask yourself

00:44:21.370 --> 00:44:27.880
why and then people will come up with different
answers: retire early, make money, find a

00:44:27.880 --> 00:44:34.310
soul mate. And then ask yourself, "Why?" again
and people will come up with the next set

00:44:34.310 --> 00:44:39.589
of answers, but if you keep asking yourself
"why?" over and over again, what's interesting

00:44:39.589 --> 00:44:43.880
is that, eventually, everyone ends up with
the same answer.

00:44:43.880 --> 00:44:48.990
And that's whatever their goal in life is,
whatever they're pursuing, they believe will

00:44:48.990 --> 00:44:55.460
make them happier. So, a couple years ago,
having nothing to do with Zappos, I started

00:44:55.460 --> 00:45:01.510
reading books and articles and so on about
this field of research that's essentially

00:45:01.510 --> 00:45:06.260
about the science of happiness. The formal
name for it is Positive Psychology. And it

00:45:06.260 --> 00:45:11.340
actually didn't exist prior to 1998, so I'm
not talking about -- go to the self-help section

00:45:11.340 --> 00:45:14.900
of a bookstore and read books that say, "Think
Positive" and you'll be happy.

00:45:14.900 --> 00:45:20.770
I'm talking about actual research that's been
done and prior to 1998, almost all of psychology

00:45:20.770 --> 00:45:24.859
was about looking at people that had something
wrong with them and then figuring out how

00:45:24.859 --> 00:45:29.609
to make them more normal. But, almost nobody
bothered to study how do you look at normal

00:45:29.609 --> 00:45:34.780
people and make them happier. So, just more
as hobby and, and everything, I thought, "Oh,

00:45:34.780 --> 00:45:35.970
that's pretty interesting."

00:45:35.970 --> 00:45:40.560
And so I started reading books and articles
on the topic and one of the consistent things

00:45:40.560 --> 00:45:44.840
that has come out of the research is that
people are very bad at predicting what will

00:45:44.840 --> 00:45:48.860
make them happy in the long term. Most people
think, "Once I get X, then I'll be happier."

00:45:48.860 --> 00:45:54.089
"Once I achieve X, then I'll be happy," when
the research shows that's not true.

00:45:54.089 --> 00:45:57.330
There's studies of lottery winners, for example.
You look at their happiness level right before

00:45:57.330 --> 00:46:01.040
winning the lottery, and then look at their
happiness level a year later. And a year later,

00:46:01.040 --> 00:46:06.130
it's the same or maybe even a little bit lower
than it was right before they won the lottery.

00:46:06.130 --> 00:46:11.560
And the reverse is true as well. There's people
that have become unexpectedly blind and you

00:46:11.560 --> 00:46:15.770
look at their happiness level a year later.
And a year later, it's actually right back

00:46:15.770 --> 00:46:18.400
to where it was before they became blind.

00:46:18.400 --> 00:46:22.040
So, I thought this was interesting and then
started thinking about it, both for my own

00:46:22.040 --> 00:46:27.870
personal life, but also for business as well,
because if people are bad at predicting what

00:46:27.870 --> 00:46:34.329
will make them happy, then us, for us trying
to build a brand around customer service,

00:46:34.329 --> 00:46:38.619
isn't just as simple as asking customers what
do they want 'cause they may not know. And

00:46:38.619 --> 00:46:42.630
same thing for employees, if we're trying
to build a culture with a lot of happy employees,

00:46:42.630 --> 00:46:47.839
you can't always just ask employees what it
is that will make them happy because they,

00:46:47.839 --> 00:46:51.780
what the research has shown is that people
are bad at predicting what will actually make

00:46:51.780 --> 00:46:52.849
them happy.

00:46:52.849 --> 00:46:57.150
And for our business and yours as well, there's
a lot of science behind, a lot of the stuff

00:46:57.150 --> 00:47:04.730
we do. We look at conversion, customer acquisition
metrics, repeat customer behavior and so on.

00:47:04.730 --> 00:47:09.770
And I don't know what the right percentage
is, but if the ultimate goal is happiness,

00:47:09.770 --> 00:47:13.810
then what percent of your time do you want
to spend studying and learning about the science

00:47:13.810 --> 00:47:18.000
of happiness? How much happier could you be
and how much could that potentially help your

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:22.849
business, whether it's in dealing with employees
or customers or vendors?

00:47:22.849 --> 00:47:27.450
A lot of people go through decades trying
to get to this ultimate destination of happiness

00:47:27.450 --> 00:47:31.790
and then when they get there, realize it's
either very short lived or maybe not even

00:47:31.790 --> 00:47:37.020
there at all. What if by studying the science
of happiness and the research that's already

00:47:37.020 --> 00:47:41.049
been done, just reading up on it a little
bit, you can kinda maybe skip some of the

00:47:41.049 --> 00:47:44.320
steps and just go straight to the happiness
part of it.

00:47:44.320 --> 00:47:45.320
[laughter]

00:47:45.320 --> 00:47:48.400
So, I thought that was interesting. So, I
just wanted to share a few different frameworks

00:47:48.400 --> 00:47:52.700
that are kind of Cliff notes version of what
I thought was interesting from the stuff that

00:47:52.700 --> 00:47:53.910
I've read about.

00:47:53.910 --> 00:47:57.570
And the first framework is that happiness
is really just about four things: perceived

00:47:57.570 --> 00:48:03.329
control, perceived progress, connectedness,
meaning the number and depth of your relationships

00:48:03.329 --> 00:48:07.900
and vision or meaning -- being part of something
bigger than yourself. And what's interesting

00:48:07.900 --> 00:48:13.180
is that you can not only apply this to your
own life, but you can apply it to business

00:48:13.180 --> 00:48:14.180
as well.

00:48:14.180 --> 00:48:19.049
So, for example, for perceived progress, in
our merchandising department, we used to hire

00:48:19.049 --> 00:48:23.040
employees entry level and then give them all
the training and mentorship and so on. They

00:48:23.040 --> 00:48:30.230
get certified and then they'd get a promotion
18 months later and then they get another

00:48:30.230 --> 00:48:33.809
set of training and certification and then
18 months after that, they'd get a promotion

00:48:33.809 --> 00:48:38.200
to become a buyer, which within Zappos is
a pretty big deal. So, it took 'em three years

00:48:38.200 --> 00:48:39.630
to become a buyer.

00:48:39.630 --> 00:48:43.760
Well, instead of giving a promotion every
18 months, we changed it a few years ago so

00:48:43.760 --> 00:48:49.390
that we gave smaller promotions every six
months. And even though nothing had changed,

00:48:49.390 --> 00:48:54.740
they still had to go through the same certification
and mentorship and training and so on, except

00:48:54.740 --> 00:48:58.490
we found that, and it still took them exactly
three years to become a buyer, but we found

00:48:58.490 --> 00:49:02.290
that because there was this ongoing sense
of perceived progress, that employees were

00:49:02.290 --> 00:49:07.540
much happier and it cost the company nothing
to do that.

00:49:07.540 --> 00:49:12.109
Another framework is Maslow's Hierarchy. There's
a great book called "Peak" by Chip Conley,

00:49:12.109 --> 00:49:18.190
P-E-A-K, where he actually condenses this
into three levels and applies it to employees

00:49:18.190 --> 00:49:25.290
and customers and investors as well. And so,
for example, for employees, the three levels

00:49:25.290 --> 00:49:29.490
of the pyramid are in terms of what they think
of their work, whether they think of it as

00:49:29.490 --> 00:49:34.819
a job versus career versus calling. And our
whole goal at Zappos is to move them up the

00:49:34.819 --> 00:49:39.299
pyramid, to think of their time at Zappos
as a calling. And we still want employees

00:49:39.299 --> 00:49:43.829
at Zappos ten years from now and the only
way that's gonna happen is if we provide all

00:49:43.829 --> 00:49:46.049
the training and mentorship and so on--

00:49:46.049 --> 00:49:47.049
[audience member coughs]

00:49:47.049 --> 00:49:49.890
so that they feel like they're growing both
personally and professionally and so we offer

00:49:49.890 --> 00:49:51.200
a lot of different classes.

00:49:51.200 --> 00:49:56.349
We have 30 or 40 different courses now and
they're not just professional courses. There's

00:49:56.349 --> 00:50:01.799
also, for example, one on the science of happiness
that, that helps them with their personal

00:50:01.799 --> 00:50:07.450
growth as well. And the last framework I wanna
share was three different types of happiness:

00:50:07.450 --> 00:50:12.530
pleasure, engagement and meaning. The first
type I like to call the "rock star" type of

00:50:12.530 --> 00:50:16.560
happiness because it's about always chasing
the next high and it's great if you can sustain

00:50:16.560 --> 00:50:17.560
it.

00:50:17.560 --> 00:50:23.540
The problem is it's very hard to sustain,
unless you're basically a rock star. And it's,

00:50:23.540 --> 00:50:27.809
it, what the research has shown is out of
these three types of happiness, a sort, as

00:50:27.809 --> 00:50:31.750
soon as your source of stimuli goes down,
goes away, your happiness level just drops

00:50:31.750 --> 00:50:34.640
right back down to where it was before.

00:50:34.640 --> 00:50:38.339
The second type is called "flow." There's
a book by the same name and it's about those

00:50:38.339 --> 00:50:42.390
moments, and we've all experienced this. For
some people it might be while running; for

00:50:42.390 --> 00:50:46.990
other people it might be painting, but it's
about when you're so into something that you're

00:50:46.990 --> 00:50:53.640
doing that three hours pass by, but it seems
like only 20 minutes have passed by. And other

00:50:53.640 --> 00:50:59.720
attributes that, that are associated with
this, are that you lose a sense of self-consciousness

00:50:59.720 --> 00:51:04.089
or even self, because you're so into what
you're doing. And professional athletes refer

00:51:04.089 --> 00:51:08.599
to it as "being in the zone" where peak performance
meets peak engagement.

00:51:08.599 --> 00:51:13.670
And kind of the strategy there is just notice
when it happens and then either change who

00:51:13.670 --> 00:51:18.680
you hang out with, your friends or your environment
or your job or where you live to try to have

00:51:18.680 --> 00:51:22.740
that type of occurrence happen more frequently.
And what the research has shown is that this

00:51:22.740 --> 00:51:27.820
is actually the second longest lasting type
of happiness. And the third type is about

00:51:27.820 --> 00:51:31.609
being part of something bigger than yourself.
And so, that might mean, for some people,

00:51:31.609 --> 00:51:36.200
volunteering for their favorite charity, for
example. And what the research has shown is

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:38.940
this is actually the longest lasting type
of happiness.

00:51:38.940 --> 00:51:42.680
So, what I thought was interesting is most
people go through life chasing after the first

00:51:42.680 --> 00:51:47.230
type, thinking, "Once I can sustain it on
an ongoing basis, which is pretty much impossible,

00:51:47.230 --> 00:51:50.910
then I'll worry about the second type and
then if I ever get around to it, then I'll

00:51:50.910 --> 00:51:55.270
worry about the third type." When, based purely
on the data from the research, the proper

00:51:55.270 --> 00:52:00.970
strategy should be "focus on the third type
of happiness first, and then layer on top

00:52:00.970 --> 00:52:05.840
of that the second type, and then the first
one, which is really just icing on the cake."

00:52:05.840 --> 00:52:09.300
So, some books that I recommend. Probably
